---
title: R108 Chicken Schnitzel with Roasted Veggies & Creamy Mustard Sauce
description: Coat pork in breadcrumbs and immediately become a mealtime MVP. Crispy pork is pretty much perfect in any form, but this isn’t your run-of-the-mill schnitzel. To amp up flavor, we’ve added lemon zest and garlic powder to our breadcrumb mixture, then drizzled the crispy pork chops with our new favorite condiment: creamy honey mustard sauce. Speaking of, we’re serving up sides of roasted potatoes and broccoli for extra dipping, but if you broke out the spoon to scrape up leftover sauce, we wouldn’t judge.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/6655f4278a4eed4f27b52f88-a44b9c9f.jpeg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/66578ff93bd4bea293f25ed2-en-US.pdf
servings: 2
cuisine: German
nutrition:
  calories: 750 kcal
  fat: 38 g
  saturated fat: 7 g
  carbohydrates: 61 g
  sugar: 14 g
  protein: 40 g
  fiber: 6 g
  sodium: 1060 mg
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/chicken-schnitzel-66578ff93bd4bea293f25ed2
time required: 35 minutes
course: main course
author: HelloFresh
---

Adjust rack to top position (top and middle positions for 4 servings) and preheat
oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch-thick wedges. Cut @broccoli{8%ounce} florets
into bite-size pieces if necessary. Zest and quarter @lemon{1}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon}, @honey{2%teaspoon}, and
@Dijon mustard{2%teaspoon}; set aside.

Toss potatoes on one side of a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @oil{}, @Fry
Seasoning{1%tablespoon}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack for
~{10%minutes}. (For 4 servings, use 2 sheets; roast potatoes on top rack and
broccoli on middle rack.)

After 10 minutes, carefully toss broccoli on empty side of baking sheet with a
drizzle of @oil{1%teaspoon}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}, and continue to roast on
top rack until veggies are browned and tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Meanwhile, place @panko breadcrumbs{1/2%cup}, lemon zest, and
@garlic powder{1%teaspoon} in a large #zip-close bag{}. Season with
@salt{1%tsp} and @pepper{}.

Pat @chicken cutlets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}.

Place @sour cream{1.5%tablespoon} in a #medium bowl{}; add pork and turn to
coat.

Place coated pork in #bag{} with panko mixture and seal to close. Shake until
pork is evenly coated.

> You may need to move pork chops around in bag, pressing with your hands, to
> spread out panko and make it stick.

Heat a 1/4-inch layer of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a large,
#heavy-bottomed pan{} over medium-high heat. Once oil is hot enough that a pinch
of panko sizzles when added to pan, add pork.

> Depending on the size of your pan, you may need to work in batches.

Cook until panko is golden and pork is cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

> For thicker pork chops, cook 1-2 minutes more.

Transfer to a #paper-towel-lined plate{}.

Divide pork, potatoes, and broccoli between plates. Serve with lemon wedges on
the side and creamy mustard sauce for dipping or drizzling.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.